article.description: Kara Braxton was happy to make the Georgia record books -- and supplant three-time U.S. Olympian Katrina McClain -- with an 11-of-11 shooting performance.
article.headline: Braxton makes all 11 shots, grabs 12 rebounds
article.linkText: Braxton's perfect night leads Georgia past Furman
article.story:
GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- Kara Braxton was happy to make the
Georgia record books -- and supplant three-time U.S. Olympian
Katrina McClain -- with an 11-of-11 shooting performance. Braxton
was even happier knowing she wouldn't have to run extra laps at
practice.

"That's my motivation," she said, laughing.

Braxton admits she gets lazy on the court sometimes. That wasn't
the case Wednesday night as the ninth-ranked Lady Dogs (7-1)
defeated Furman 86-51. Braxton, who tied her season high with 22
points, sprinted out in front for easy baskets and, when Furman's
defense collapsed, was there to clean up the misses.

Braxton had 12 rebounds for her fifth double-double this season.

Her perfect shooting topped the school's mark set by McClain,
the national player of the year in 1987, who went 11-of-12 against
Stephen F. Austin in 1984.

"She is big time for our program," Braxton said. "It's an
honor to be up there with her."

And, if you listen to Braxton, it may not be the last such
performance.

"I am capable, it's just a point of pushing myself," she said.

Despite the stats, things hadn't gone so well for Braxton this
season. She was only 8-of-19 from the field against Houston and
missed eight of her 13 attempts in Georgia's last game against
Middle Tennessee.

In the team's only loss, 61-59 at Stanford, Braxton was only
6-of-11 with seven rebounds.

"That's why were not 8-0," Georgia coach Andy Landers said.

"It's tough when you're this tall and miss shots under the
basket," she said.

In fact, Landers had Braxton watch additional film of her misses
-- when she wasn't running -- to see "some of her sins," he said.

The extra work paid off.

"She's so blessed with size and agility and speed," Landers
said. "And when you have people with attributes like that, they
usually have special nights like she had tonight."

Besides Braxton's inside dominance, the Lady Dogs showed off an
aggressive and forceful defense to swamp their Southern Conference
opponents and improve to 6-0 all-time against Furman.

The Lady Paladins (3-3) had turnovers on five of their first six
possessions as they fell behind 8-2 in the first three minutes.

After Kim Lawrence hit a 3-pointer to draw Furman within 17-14,
Georgia went on a 21-2 run over the next 10 minutes to lead 38-16.

Sherill Baker had six points during the run and Braxton added
two baskets in the spurt.

Georgia forced 18 turnovers in taking a 40-19 halftime lead and
were up by as many as 39 points in the final few minutes.

Baker added 14 points for Georgia and Christi Thomas had 13.

Lawrence had 15 points for Furman, while Deshara Shealey, the
Lady Paladins' leading scorer coming in, was held to 4-of-14
shooting and 10 points.

About the only second-half drama for Georgia was whether Braxton
would miss. After going 4-of-4 in the first half, she made four
more in the first 4:26 after the break. Another inside shot gave
Braxton her ninth straight field goal before coach Andy Landers
rested her for about five minutes.

Braxton came in again, hitting a layup with 7:40 to go to put
Georgia up 69-35. Her 11th and final shot came about a minute later
and Braxton left the game for good.

Her only flaw? Braxton missed both of her foul shots.

"It's hard to stop 6-6 when she's shooting like that," Furman
coach Sam Dixon said.

Landers could sure use Braxton to put up similar numbers this
Saturday when the Lady Bulldogs travel to No. 5 Texas. Braxton
thinks things might be easier now that she's gotten on track.

"This game I just let it come to me," Braxton said. "I'm real
happy with our overall game and not just the individual stats."
